dividual_id":"019d0a11-4d30-77b1-a76e-9b43c33599f2","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Shannon Cheng","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Control Pickup","individual_id":"019b7b13-3219-7a2c-93f7-0d0d45e15e8e","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Sue Kuestner","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Course Designer","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d2f-7780-8db0-47a6d8b7327c","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Ethan O'Connor","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Course Designer","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d30-77b1-a76e-9b43c33599f2","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Shannon Cheng","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Course Designer(s)","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d2f-7780-8db0-47a6d8b7327c","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Ethan O'Connor","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Course Designer(s)","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d30-77b1-a76e-9b43c33599f2","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Shannon Cheng","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Finish","individual_id":"01913919-da03-757e-b829-aa2bdc684400","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Debbie Newell","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Finish","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d2f-736d-863f-5e546e61e969","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Ing Uhlin","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Meet Director","individual_id":"019d0a40-c41c-7534-9c1e-89cf1709d9d0","citation_count":2,"individual_name":"Jud Kelley","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Newcomer Instruction","individual_id":"019d0a40-c41f-7fda-bfea-19eff1fa35ec","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Stan Woods","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Registration","individual_id":"019b7ac9-920b-70bb-8a36-b4b700fb52d4","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Ardis Dull","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Registration","individual_id":"019b7adf-f250-735f-9fc9-46fd3e9119b1","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Marjorie Stratton","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Start","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d30-7f45-a013-aa5603e6c1ac","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Joanne Woods","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Start","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d30-77b1-a76e-9b43c33599f2","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Shannon Cheng","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null}],"organizing_club_id":"01912f3e-e3e1-7e8e-b3c6-32387a8b4990","result_source_brief":"CascadeOC Website: https://cascadeoc.org/result/2019-ultimate-orienteer-9-fishtrap-lake-ultralong/","organizing_club_name":"Cascade Orienteering Club","cumulative_event_comments":"Download a PDF with details for both the Classic and Ultralong events.\nOur 3rd full weekend of orienteering in this year’s Ultimate Series!\nThe Season Finale (UO #9) will be an Ultralong Distance event at Fishtrap Lake, following the Classic Distance event at Riverside State Park in Spokane the day before organized by EWOC.\nTerrain\nExperience the unique scabland terrain of Fishtrap Lake, where the vistas are expansive but details are plentiful. There are few trails in this area, so you’ll appreciate the plethora of contour and rock details as you traverse this beautiful desert area. June is a great time of year for wildflowers here, so you might want to take a moment to enjoy them.\nOut of Bounds areas\n–Ethan O’Connor, Shannon Cheng\nCome out to Fishtrap! This final event of the 2019 Ultimate series is the Ultralong and we were charged with creating courses that emphasize endurance, route choice and rough map reading. Please take a careful look at the estimated distance of your course and plan to start as early in the start window as is practical for you.\nWe Fishtrap in late May amidst a spectacular display of wildflowers and were reminded of how beautiful and special a place it is. We had an enjoyable time re-visiting the unique landscape and hope that the courses we’ve set provide everyone a sampler of all the terrain has to offer.\nIn late May we found comparatively wet conditions. Updated information will be provided at the Start but it would be safe to assume water is on the high end of what is mapped. The areas of the map marked as runnable forest that burned a few years ago have largely grown over with annoying-to-impenetrable new growth, and the courses this year avoid most of that terrain. Lone trees are extensively mapped and are a particularly helpful navigation aid outside of the burned areas. Trails vary considerably in visibility but we were able to locate and follow those mapped trails we came across. Linear rock features and the gaps therein are very well mapped and are key to navigating in this terrain.\nThere will be some unavoidable fence crossings – in most cases, you can find easier spots to cross by walking along the length. We were able to crawl under most – taller people may be able to step over. In any situation, please be careful, especially at those with barbed wire.\n\nDownload a PDF with details for both the Classic and Ultralong events.\nOur 3rd full weekend of orienteering in this year’s Ultimate Series!\nThe Season Finale (UO #9) will be an Ultralong Distance event at Fishtrap Lake, following the Classic Distance event at Riverside State Park in Spokane the day before organized by EWOC.\nExperience the unique scabland terrain of Fishtrap Lake, where the vistas are expansive but details are plentiful. There are few trails in this area, so you’ll appreciate the plethora of contour and rock details as you traverse this beautiful desert area. June is a great time of year for wildflowers here, so you might want to take a moment to enjoy them.\nMost of the area we’re using belongs to the Bureau of Land Management. They have identified several sensitive areas, which are out of bounds for our competition. These areas are clearly marked on the map with vertical purple lines. The courses have been designed to avoid them, so make sure your route choice does not include travel through ANY out of bounds areas!\nMountain biking is only allowed for control pickup, so if you want to ride your bike, please volunteer to pick up controls after the event is over.\n–Ethan O’Connor, Shannon Cheng\nCome out to Fishtrap! This final event of the 2019 Ultimate series is the Ultralong and we were charged with creating courses that emphasize endurance, route choice and rough map reading. Please take a careful look at the estimated distance of your course and plan to start as early in the start window as is practical for you.\nWe Fishtrap in late May amidst a spectacular display of wildflowers and were reminded of how beautiful and special a place it is. We had an enjoyable time re-visiting the unique landscape and hope that the courses we’ve set provide everyone a sampler of all the terrain has to offer.\nIn late May we found comparatively wet conditions. Updated information will be provided at the Start but it would be safe to assume water is on the high end of what is mapped. The areas of the map marked as runnable forest that burned a few years ago have largely grown over with annoying-to-impenetrable new growth, and the courses this year avoid most of that terrain. Lone trees are extensively mapped and are a particularly helpful navigation aid outside of the burned areas. Trails vary considerably in visibility but we were able to locate and follow those mapped trails we came across. Linear rock features and the gaps therein are very well mapped and are key to navigating in this terrain.\nThere will be some unavoidable fence crossings – in most cases, you can find easier spots to cross by walking along the length. We were able to crawl under most – taller people may be able to step over. In any situation, please be careful, especially at those with barbed wire."}
